pr_review_comment_body:
Yeah. We should also provide a utility function for building the object, following the pattern we have with the networking data structures (e.g. `create_ipam_pool`):

```python
def create_healthcheck(test=None, interval=None, timeout=None, retries=None):
    return {
        'Test': test,
        'Interval': interval,
        'Timeout': timeout,
        'Retries': retries,
    }
```

This finally has correct alignment, but apparently this part was not valid from the very beginning: `} for` has the same indentation as `]`, but `{…}` is *deeper* and thus cannot have the same indentation. This should be

```Python
return [
    {
        'contents': w['name'][strip:],
        'highlight_groups': calcgrp(w)
    }
    for w in get_i3_connection().get_workspaces()
    if (
        (not only_show or any((w[typ] for typ in only_show)))
        and (not output or w['output'] == output)
    )
]
```

Replace four spaces with tabs and do not mess with alignment at all.

Though no, I will change this myself just in case.

You can officially call this doomed list comprehension. clint.py from Neovim with my recently merged modifications would have caught this, but it is for C.

---

BTW, I was enclosing generator in another level of parenthesis always since the very beginning, because something was failing with syntax from your code in Python-2.6. But Python documentation shows that this syntax is OK from [Python-2.4](https://docs.python.org/2.6/whatsnew/2.4.html) where it was introduced. Do you have any idea what was failing?

if (!can_get_value(v))) return false;
lp::var_index vi = m_theory_var2var_index[v];

…

if (m_solver->has_lower_bound(vi, ci, val, is_strict))
...

Why not just initialize self.entities and self.metadata here instead?  I.e.
if entities is None:
    self.entities = []
else:
    self.entities = entities
if metadata is None:
    self.metadata = {}
else:
    self.metadata = metadata

From that point on you know those have been properly constructed and you don't have to do all the checks below on each usage.

I think we could simplify the above logic and avoid the need for defining this new `Set()` method by simply declaring a struct above.  For example:

```c
    if (aDataset.mIsChannelMaskPage0Set)
    {
        OT_TOOL_PACKED_BEGIN
        struct
        {
            MeshCoP::ChannelMaskTlv tlv;
            MeshCoP::ChannelMaskEntry entry;
            uint8_t mask[4];
        } OT_TOOL_PACKED_END channelMask;

        ...

        Set(channelMask.tlv);

        ...

    }
```

Hmmm...... should `array_t::itemsize()` be constexpr, ignoring `descr->elsize` and using `sizeof(T)`? Not sure.

If it is, would this work?

```
size_t array::Itemsize() const {
        return (size_t) PyArrayDescr_GET_(PyArray_GET_(m_ptr, descr), elsize);
}

template<typename T, int flags> constexpr size_t array_t::itemsize() const {
    return sizeof(T);  // ?
}

...

offset_at(index...) / itemsize()
```
